orfolk,England.":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Freville","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French (<b>Préville</b>): habitational name from (La) Préville, the name of several places in various parts of France."],"variants":[{"name":"Previl","meanings":["Haitian (<b>Prévil</b>):","alternatively, perhaps a shortened form of French <b>Préville</b> (see   Preville  ).","ornamental name composed of French <i>pré</i> ‘meadow’ and a shortened form of <i>ville</i> ‘settlement’ (see   Vil  )."]}]},{"name":"Roger","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["1  ♂ ‘Wondrous’ or ‘enlightenment’.","2  ♀ ‘Fine jade’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Dev ."],"variants":[{"name":"Deborah","meanings":["Biblical name (meaning ‘bee’ in Hebrew), borne by the nurse of Rebecca (Genesis 35:8) and by a woman judge and prophet (Judges 4–5) who led the Israelites to victory over the Canaanites. It has always been popular as a Jewish name. It was in use among Christians by the mid 16th century and was taken up by the Puritans in the 17th century, in part because the bee was a symbol of industriousness. Since then it has enjoyed enormous popularity, peaking in the 1960s. Among other famous bearers is the actress  Deborah Kerr  (  1921–2007 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Roger II de Freville was born about 1119, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, his father, Manasser d'Aguillon, was 1 and his mother, Eleanor de Marmion, was 4. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Sybil FitzAlan. He died about 1160, in Wolston, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"about 1119–about 1160":"umbes 1119–umbes 1160","1119–1160":"1119–1160","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1140–1206":"1140–1206","1109–Female":"1109–Surnud","1151–Male":"1151–Surnud","1153–Female":"1153–Surnud","1120–1195":"1120–1195","1117–1167":"1117–1167","about 1160":"umbes 1160","1120":"1120","1153":"1153","1195":"1195","1151":"1151","1140":"1140","1160":"1160","Abt 1153":"umbes 1153","1206":"1206","1117":"1117","Abt 1151":"umbes 1151","about 1119":"umbes 1119","1167":"1167","1200":"1200","1109":"1109","1119":"1119","of Wolston,Warwick,England":"Wolston, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolston, Warwickshire, England":"Wolston, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolston,Warwickshire,England.":"Wolston, Warwickshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom",",Norfolk,England.":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1119–about 1160":"noin 1119–noin 1160","1119–1160":"1119–1160","1140–1200":"1140–1200","1140–1206":"1140–1206","1109–Female":"1109–Kuollut","1151–Male":"1151–Kuollut","1153–Female":"1153–Kuollut","1120–1195":"1120–1195","1117–1167":"1117–1167","about 1160":"noin 1160","1120":"1120","1153":"1153","1195":"1195","1151":"1151"